story10 = Story.new(title: "Gustave Caillebotte's Portrait of Henri Cordier", category: "Art", author_id: user8.id, body: "<p>Esteemed scholar Henri Cordier is seated at a handsome chestnut desk in his cramped Parisian study, comfortably leaning over a stack of papers with quill in hand. An immediate intimacy is established with the academic, whose back is partially turned toward the viewer, inviting the eye to look over his left shoulder and into the scene. Cordier’s face is rendered in complete profile and his body is hunched toward the sheet he is writing on, putting his head and chest physically close to his hands as he writes. Cordier’s notes appear blurry and illegible at a distance, but it is understood that his project requires great concentration and thought. His heavy-lidded eyes are cast down, wholly absorbed in his work, as his quill moves across the paper. His greying dark hair and beard appear to be slightly disheveled, as if he recently ran his fingers through his hair in a moment of deep contemplation.\n 
It is a quiet, meditative space. Bookshelves laden with heavy volumes of texts and sets of encyclopedias line the walls, physically surrounding Cordier as he diligently works. To his right, lavishly colored volumes of books fill the shelves and another bookshelf behind the desk, partially hidden by a thick collection of quills, holds even more volumes. The scholar’s grey suit appears to reflect and mimic the vivid reds, greys, blues, and purples of the books, resulting in a reddish-purple tinge emanating from the fabric. The dominant presence of the bookshelves is a testament to Cordier’s career and implies that the literary man is regularly consumed by his scholarship.\n 
The worn black surface of the wooden desk is adorned with a variety of objects, some of which are further signifiers of Cordier’s commitment to his research. Toward the back of the desk, opposite Cordier, is a small faceless military figurine painted in primary colors. Barely discernable, its uniform is composed of a navy blue jacket and red underclothes, and the figure is armed with a golden spear, shield, and two-pronged helmet. The figurine is propped against a number of different sized sheets of loose white paper, a large yellowed envelope, and leather bound books. The arrangement of these items in a state of mild disarray suggests that Cordier is often at work in his study and possibly referenced one of these papers or books just moments ago.\n 
Directly behind the papers are two loose bundles of long, cream-colored quills, presumably arranged in containers hidden at the edge of the desk. A highly ornate lamp rests upon the far right corner of the desk, casting a purple shadow onto some of the nearby quills. The lamp’s luminous gold color is intensified by light radiating from its bulb, illuminating a motif of figures carved in low sculptural relief. A fine, elaborate beige fringe hangs from the perimeter of the delicate lace lampshade, almost melding with the adjacent assemblage of quills. The lamp’s light, most importantly, highlights the face of Cordier and the text he is drafting, casting a spotlight on the scholar hard at work in his confined study.
</p>")

file = File.open('app/assets/images/HenriCordier.jpg')
story10.image = file
story10.save!

story11 = Story.new(category: "Art", author_id: user1.id, title: "A Spanish Masterpiece, a Self-Portrait and an Ontological Puzzle", body: "
  <p>After investigating the overwhelming body of scholarly literature that has been written about Velazquez’s Las Meninas (Fig. 1), it is clear that there is no one approach to the painting or interpretation of its significance that scholars have agreed on in the 20th and 21st centuries. Rather, this work of art created in 17th century Spain and housed today in the Museo del Prado in Madrid has been examined in many ways revealing a wide variety of possible meanings. Some examine its iconographical significance and see it as a visual argument for the liberal art of painting as well as an attempt by its painter, Diego Velazquez, to ennoble not just the field of painting, but by extension himself as a friend of the King and an important court official who was seeking membership into the prestigious Order of Santiago. Other scholars observe the painting from a philosophical view focusing on the unique approach to perspective that Velazquez employs in the work. Yet another group of scholars do not focus on examining the painting itself, but rather seek to explore its reception history in Western Europe and the United States during the 19th century.\n 
Nonetheless, one reoccurring theme which a vast majority of scholars all address is the painting’s ability to capture the attention of the viewer and inspire him or her to attempt a new interpretation of the work. Indeed, one of the most fascinating things about reading all of the scholarly literature on Las Meninas is the variety of disciplines that seek to tackle this famous Spanish painting. From Foucault’s philosophical approach, to Hamann’s anthropological study to Brown’s art historical discussion, it is clear that the painting does not only belong to the field of art history. Interestingly enough, none of these authors view their own interpretations as sufficient and instead acknowledge that the work cannot be explained in any one analysis. Velazquez specialist, Suzanne Stratton-Pruitt, notes that “there is no last word” on Las Meninas.  While Art Historian, Leo Steinberg, claims that writing about Las Meninas is “somewhat comparable to the performing of a great musical composition of which there are no definitive renderings” viewing his own article as one of an infinite series of scholarly attempts to find meaning in the painting that all result in “guaranteed inadequac(ies).”\n    
Yet it is this continual reinterpretation of the painting, as Jonathan Brown remarks in his essay “On the Meaning of Las Meninas,” that keeps it alive.  To Brown, the painting’s greatest attribute does not lay in any one correct meaning, but rather in its power to be continually viewed by scholars as a masterpiece worthy of further discussion and interpretation. As such, the following essay adds yet another voice to this process of “perpetual revitalization”   of the work by outlining the many and diverse ways in which scholars have constructed meaning in Las Meninas and suggesting ideas for further research and interpretation surrounding this Spanish masterpiece heading into the 21st century.</p>
")

file = File.open('app/assets/images/LasMeninas.png')
story11.image = file
story11.save!

story12 = Story.new(category: "Science", title: "There’s a lot of money up for grabs if you can land (softly) on the moon", author_id: user4.id, body: "<p>If you can send a spacecraft to the moon and loop around our natural satellite one time, or—even better—gently set a rover down on the lunar surface, there could be money in it for you. $4.75 million, to be precise.\n 
  That is, if you happen to be one of the select few finalist teams competing for the Google Lunar XPrize. The awarding organizations—Xprize and Google—have decided to split two prize amounts between whatever teams manage to achieve two distinct feats: \n $1.75 million is up for grabs as part of the Lunar Arrival Milestone Prize. To get a slice of that pie, a “spacecraft must complete one orbit around the moon or enter a direct descent approach to the lunar surface,” according to press materials supplied by XPrize.
A larger chunk—three million dollars—will be split between spacecraft that win the Soft Landing Milestone Prize. To win that, the awarding foundation says that a 'spacecraft must transmit data proving it soft-landed on the lunar surface.'\n 
Both of those achievements must be met before March 31, 2018, which is also the new deadline by which teams must complete their attempt at the $30 million Grand Prize. The Grand Prize goes to the first team that manages to put a robot on the moon, explore for 500 meters, and send high-def images and video back to Earth. There will also be a smaller prize for the second team to meet those goals. The catch? The teams need to be 90 percent privately funded.\n 
Robotic exploration of our solar system has long been the purview of national space agencies, which spend millions, and sometimes billions of dollars on developing new technologies. The Curiosity Rover, for example, cost about $2.6 billion (not a lot when you consider the length of the mission, but still pretty expensive). This competition is an attempt to find cheaper ways of exploring the space around us. Previous privately funded missions, like 4M back in 2014, have been relatively simple in design—and none have landed on the lunar surface.\n 
Five teams so far have secured contracts to launch their spacecraft; SpaceIL, Moon Express, Synergy Moon, TeamIndus, and HAKUTO. They all have official plans to launch something by the end of 2017, which is going to make for an exciting next few months in space news, but they now have a few extra months to complete their mission.
It’s a sweet prize, but getting a share of the money won’t be easy. After all, it actually is rocket science.</p>")

file = File.open('app/assets/images/moon.png')
story12.image = file 
story12.save!

story13 = Story.new(category: "Travel", title: "This 'New' Swiss Hotel Is Actually 140 Years Old", author_id: user3.id, body: "<p>Ninety minutes from Zurich, this hotel and spa is hidden in plain sight.\n
  Switzerland’s storied hotels, while lovely, often blend together in a Swiss-neutral haze. The by-the-numbers rooms in Gstaad and Klosters lean heavily on Alpine nostalgia, while even the splashy lounges in St. Moritz are stocked with hunting lodge armchairs and armoires. But inside one of these grand hotels, you'll find a surprise: the glitziest new resort in the Alps, in a 140-year-old building, no less. \n 
  Located 90 minutes southwest of Zurich amid buttercup fields, pine trees, and concertinaing mountains, the Waldhaus Flims Hotel and Spa went bankrupt in 2015, but American equity investor Z Capital scooped the property up and recently completed its first phase of a $40 million plan to amp up the hotel's luxury. Debuting this past June with little fanfare, the revamped lobby and 142 reimagined rooms now feature bubble lamps, Swiss modern art, and a custom marigold-and-cocoa color palette. The makeover also includes ritzy common rooms, glass-encased fireplaces, a swanky library, and an extensive renovation of the original Belle Epoque pavilion, now home to a ballroom, prosecco bar, and an unapologetically Swiss farm-to-fork restaurant. Specialties include Alpine sturgeon, braised venison, and cheese from the canton of Grisons. (If cheese is really your thing, the hotel also has a restaurant devoted to just that.) Next up? A soon-to-follow medical wellness center.</p>")

file = File.open('app/assets/images/swiss_hotel.jpg')
story13.image = file 
story13.save!

story14 = Story.new(category: "Travel", title: "Why Greece Is Best Seen by Boat
", author_id: user8.id, body: "<p>A traditional Turkish gulet allows a lot of freedom and flexibility.\n 
The summertime appeal of Greece—languid Mediterreanean lunches, charming white-washed villages, hidden swimming coves—can undoubtedly be spoiled by the crowds. But if you look beyond the well- trodden spots (and know how to navigate the Aegean) you’ll happen upon a smattering of tiny isles with all the spoils of the popular spots like Mykonos and Santorini, but without the tourists.\n
Looking to avoid those crowds, my partner and I booked one of the eight cabins aboard Sailing Cruise in Comfort's (SCIC) traditional wooden gulet—two-mast Turkish sailing vessels. Once used for fishing, these boats can now ferry up to 16 passengers for week-long tours through the southern Greek islands and Turkish coastline. The appeal is two-fold: Gulets give you greater access to the more remote islands, since their size allows them to dock in shallower waters, as well as spontaneity—the SCIC itineraries are dictated literally by where the wind blows. “Most other charters in these parts treat their sails as window-dressing,” explains Captain Oktay Yilmaz, “instead relying on their 360-horsepower Diesel engines.” The SCIC sails are raised to catch whatever gust is coming through, so you don’t necessarily know which islands you’ll end up on.\n 
Our first gale (and Yilmaz’s skilled steering) brought us to the Nisyros, home to just over a 1000 residents and one brooding active volcano, Polyvotis. We docked in the sleepy harbor town of Mandraki early enough to watch the local taverna owners open up for the day, and drove up the island’s steep winding roads to the smoldering caldera. According to Greek mythology, Nisyros was once attached to Kos, but Poseidon split the isle in two when a battle between the Gods and the Titans broke out. These days the island is pretty tranquil. Along the crater, the brilliant white-and-blue houses and slumbering tabbys of the tiny village of Nikia serve as the postcard-perfect backdrop for sipping soumada, the traditional Greek almond soft drink served at one of the town's two tavernas.</p>")

file = File.open('app/assets/images/greece.jpg')
story14.image = file 
story14.save!

story15 = Story.new(category: "Food", title: "How and Where to Fika in Stockholm
", author_id: user6.id, body: "<p>The city is the capital of the coffee break.\n 
Fika, or the act of taking a break over coffee and a snack, is a Swedish tradition that, at its roots, encourages people to pause and reset. Contrary to grabbing a cup of joe to go, in Sweden, fika is a time where you're obliged to forget everything, at least for a little while, and savor the present—preferably over a piping-hot cup of coffee.\n 
“It’s the moment of the day you share with someone you really like or someone you want to know better,” says Arman Seropian, co-owner of Café Pascal in Stockholm.\n 
Sweden consumes 18 pounds of the stuff per capita, per year—about 864 cups a person. But just as important as the drinks are the treats that are paired with them, which can range from classic Swedish pastries like kanelbulle (a twisty cinnamon bun sans frosting), chokladboll (an uncooked chocolate ball rolled in coconut flakes), and semlor (a cream puff-like bun filled with fluffy marzipan and whipped cream), to trendy, more savory treats like avocado toast.\n 
The crucial thing about fika, though, is that you make time to slow down. Swedes fika (it’s a verb and a noun) most commonly around 11 a.m., but can fika several times a day—yes, even during the work week. They may be on to something: According to the United Nations' 2017 World Happiness Report, Sweden ranks in the top ten countries whose inhabitants are happiest (and friendliest).\n 
Stockholm in particular is home to hundreds of uber-stylish cafes whose Scandinavian design is often part of their draw, especially for tourists. “For us, [the aesthetic and design] is super important as that’s part of the vibe you sense when you enter the café,” says Seropian, though Green Rabbit chef Mathias Dahlgren is quick to point out that the focus is really about “a good cup of coffee and sitting down for a couple of minutes with friends, family, and co-workers.” Unsurprisingly, both cafés have seen in an increase in foreign visitors who are eager to try out fika for themselves.</p>")

