story16 = Story.new(category: "Food", title: "Why You Should Eat Rice—Not Pasta—in Milan", author_id: user4.id, body: "<p>Where to eat the classic risotto alla Milanese in Milan, plus, what to avoid.\n
Many travelers immediately think of Italy as the land of pizza, pasta and hunks of fresh cheese, but it actually produces the lion’s share of Europe’s rice—and has quite a history with it. The grain first surfaced in Italy in the 13th century via the conquering Moors, who introduced it to Sicily. From there, the crop made its way to Naples and the ruling family then sent it north, to be harvested in the Po Valley, near Milan. In the “rice bowl of Italy,” the grain grows easily thanks to higher humidity, lots of water, and a flat landscape.\n “The Milanese have perfected a way to cook the rice, which is the risotto. Growing up, it was always on the table,” Andrea Oschetti, the Milanese chef behind Blueflower experiential food and travel service, tells Condé Nast Traveler. 'If you pay close attention to the simplicity and quality of ingredients of a good risotto, you can understand the essence of the culture.'\n 
Made with vibrant yellow saffron and bit of bone marrow for good measure, risotto alla Milanese is a staple on traditional menus. While ubiquitous now, it was actually invented on a whim. During the construction of the Milan Cathedral in the 16th century, a cook is said to have added saffron to mimic the sunny stained glass windows...and it stuck.\n 
“This is a simple dish to make—all you need is a great broth, rice, Parmesan cheese, and some butter. But the fundamental for a traditional risotto alla Milanese is bone marrow,” says Oschetti. 'Just a little bit. Not a lot. It gives the taste a kick.'</p>")

